CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is used to control the presentation of web pages. It allows you to change the layout, colors, fonts, and more. Letâ€™s explore the basics.

## Syntax of CSS

A CSS rule consists of a selector and a declaration block. For example:

```css
h1 {
  color: blue;
  font-size: 24px;
}
```

This will make all `<h1>` elements blue and set the font size to 24 pixels.

## Selectors in CSS

CSS selectors target HTML elements to apply styles. Here are some common ones:

1. **Element Selector**: Targets all elements of a specific type:

```css
p {
  color: red;
}
```

2. **Class Selector**: Targets elements with a specific class:

```css
.text-bold {
  font-weight: bold;
}
```

3. **ID Selector**: Targets a single element with a unique ID:

```css
#main-header {
  background-color: yellow;
}
```

## Box Model in CSS

The box model is essential in understanding CSS layout. Every HTML element is treated as a box, consisting of margins, borders, padding, and content.

### Conclusion

CSS provides immense power to control the appearance of web pages. By mastering selectors, the box model, and styling techniques, you can create visually appealing and responsive websites.
